Assistant to the President for Homeland Security and Counterterrorism, John Brennan, visited Libya and met with senior Libyan officials, including President Magariaf. He expressed President Obama's support for Libya's government formation and transition to democracy and offered condolences for the deaths of four Americans in Benghazi. The two sides discussed the ongoing investigation into the Benghazi attacks and steps Libya can take to assist in bringing the perpetrators to justice. Both sides reaffirmed their commitment to countering terrorism. Brennan encouraged Libyan officials to improve their policies and capabilities in the security and justice sectors and urged them to take advantage of assistance from the United States and other international partners. He also reiterated the United States' support for the Libyan people and their leaders in their efforts towards governance and reform.